   "source": [
    "### Calculate and Plot Beta for a chosen portfolio and the S&P 60 TSX"

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

   "source": [
    "# Calculate covariance of a single portfolio\n",
    "cov_algo1 = combined_return['Algo 1'].rolling(window = 60).cov(combined_return['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "# Calculate variance of S&P TSX\n",
    "sp_var = combined_return['S&P_TSX'].rolling(window = 60).var()\n",
    "# Computing beta\n",
    "beta = cov_algo1 / sp_var\n",
    "# Plot beta trend\n",
    "beta.plot(figsize = (22,8), title = \"Choosen Portfolio : Algo 1\")"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Rolling Statistics Challenge: Exponentially Weighted Average \n",
    "\n",
    "An alternative way to calculate a rolling window is to take the exponentially weighted moving average. This is like a moving window average, but it assigns greater importance to more recent observations. Try calculating the [`ewm`](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.ewm.html) with a 21-day half-life."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Date'>"

    },

     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Use `ewm` to calculate the rolling window\n",
    "cov_algo1_ewm = combined_return['Algo 1'].ewm(halflife = 21).cov(combined_return['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "sp_var_ewm = combined_return['S&P_TSX'].ewm(halflife = 21).var()\n",
    "beta_ewm = cov_algo1_ewm/sp_var_ewm\n",
    "beta_ewm.plot(figsize = (22,8))"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Sharpe Ratios\n",
    "In reality, investment managers and thier institutional investors look at the ratio of return-to-risk, and not just returns alone. After all, if you could invest in one of two portfolios, and each offered the same 10% return, yet one offered lower risk, you'd take that one, right?\n",
    "\n",
    "### Using the daily returns, calculate and visualize the Sharpe ratios using a bar plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 139,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Algo 1                         1.491514\n",
      "BERKSHIRE HATHAWAY INC         0.467045\n",
      "Algo 2                         0.396817\n",
      "SOROS FUND MANAGEMENT LLC      0.286709\n",
      "S&P_TSX                        0.195550\n",
      "TIGER GLOBAL MANAGEMENT LLC   -0.144455\n",
      "PAULSON & CO.INC.             -0.547594\n",
      "dtype: float64\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "the highest sharpe ratio of Algo 1 : 1.491514 suggests highest profit\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Annualized Sharpe Ratios\n",
    "combined_std_annual = combined_return.std() * np.sqrt(252)\n",
    "combined_sharpe_ratios = (combined_return.mean() * 252) / (combined_std_annual)\n",
    "combined_sharpe_ratios.sort_values(ascending = False, inplace = True)\n",
    "print(combined_sharpe_ratios)\n",
    "print('\\n')\n",
    "print(f'the highest sharpe ratio of Algo 1 : {round(combined_sharpe_ratios.max(),6)} suggests highest profit')"
   ]

    "### Determine whether the algorithmic strategies outperform both the market (S&P TSX 60) and the whales portfolios.\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Its true that the Algo Strategies has outperformed the S&P and the whales portfolio, especialy when it comes to Algo 1 stock"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Create Custom Portfolio\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, you will build your own portfolio of stocks, calculate the returns, and compare the results to the Whale Portfolios and the S&P TSX 60. \n",
    "\n",
    "1. Choose 3-5 custom stocks with at last 1 year's worth of historic prices and create a DataFrame of the closing prices and dates for each stock.\n",
    "2. Calculate the weighted returns for the portfolio assuming an equal number of shares for each stock.\n",
    "3. Join your portfolio returns to the DataFrame that contains all of the portfolio returns.\n",
    "4. Re-run the performance and risk analysis with your portfolio to see how it compares to the others.\n",
    "5. Include correlation analysis to determine which stocks (if any) are correlated."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

    "### Calculate and Plot the 60-day Rolling Beta for Your Portfolio compared to the S&P 60 TSX"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 157,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x23333558cc8>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 157,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1584x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Calculate and plot Beta\n",
    "my_both_df = both_df[['loblaw_close', 'shopify_close', 'open_close', 'portfolio_return']]\n",
    "my_cov_loblaw = my_both_df['loblaw_close'].rolling(window = 60).cov(both_df['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "my_cov_open = my_both_df['open_close'].rolling(window = 60).cov(both_df['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "my_cov_shopify = my_both_df['shopify_close'].rolling(window = 60).cov(both_df['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "my_cov_overall = my_both_df['portfolio_return'].rolling(window = 60).cov(both_df['S&P_TSX'])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate variance of S&P TSX\n",
    "sp_var = both_df['S&P_TSX'].rolling(window = 60).var()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Computing beta\n",
    "my_beta_loblaw = my_cov_loblaw / sp_var\n",
    "my_beta_open = my_cov_open / sp_var\n",
    "my_beta_shopify = my_cov_shopify / sp_var\n",
    "my_beta_overall = my_cov_overall / sp_var\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot beta trend\n",
    "ax = my_beta_loblaw.plot(figsize = (22,8), title = 'Overall Beta in comparison with individual stock Beta')\n",
    "my_beta_open.plot(ax = ax)\n",
    "my_beta_shopify.plot(ax = ax)\n",
    "my_beta_overall.plot(ax = ax)\n",
    "ax.legend(['LOBLAW', 'OPEN_TEXT', 'SHOPIFY', 'OVERALL_RETURN'])"
   ]
  },
